> I think the way to go is to lock all the elements within a group, and when selecting a group we'd check if all elements within a group are locked → if yes, then prevent group selection.

@dwelle Just thinking about this some more, I think this might lead to some confusing behaviour... I can group two elements and then lock one of them. What you describe would allow movement of the locked sibling in the canvas which I don't think is correct.

Miro solves this by removing the element from it's group when it goes into a locked state. It can do this without being confusing because Miro doesn't allow nested groups. An excalidraw element would need to "pop out" of all ancestor groups which seems confusing.

@jcezarms I'm glad to hear this works so reliably for you.  On a technical note, #2993/#5311 provide MathJax support as an "extension" rather than a "plugin".  Per discussions with @dwelle, extensions are reviewed by the Excalidraw team, whereas plugins are community-made without review from Excalidraw.

I can not say for certain, but I believe the answer to your question would be, #2993 mainly just needs review by someone from @excalidraw.  (I doubt it would take much work to put extensions on subdomains like "math.excalidraw.com".  Also, I provided a way to select which extensions get loaded.)

